430
00:30:22,640 --> 00:30:23,162
Scott: Guess what?

431
00:30:23,704 --> 00:30:27,580
Scott: Both of those cables are exactly identical in function.

432
00:30:28,141 --> 00:30:32,507
Rym: Yes, and even worse are when people try to pass off digital cables as different.

433
00:30:32,848 --> 00:30:35,252
Rym: A digital cable is a digital cable.

434
00:30:35,552 --> 00:30:39,298
Rym: The signal either gets all the way there, or it never gets there.

435
00:30:39,358 --> 00:30:40,760
Rym: There is no middle ground.

436
00:30:41,040 --> 00:30:48,060
Scott: Yeah, on an analog cable, just so we can get this straight, you're sending an electrical wave over the wire.

437
00:30:48,461 --> 00:30:51,020
Rym: So if the cable's poorly shielded or something, you could get interference.

438
00:30:51,020 --> 00:30:54,893
Scott: Yes, it is possible for there to be interference on that wire.

439
00:30:54,953 --> 00:31:00,159
Scott: You'll know if, like, your speakers are going like... Then there's probably interference going on.

440
00:31:00,440 --> 00:31:05,619
Rym: However, the lie here is that the so-called better cables aren't actually any better, but anyway...

441
00:31:05,780 --> 00:31:12,651
Scott: Yes, but digital cables, all they're doing is going zero, one, zero, one, one, one, zero, one, and you know what?

442
00:31:13,312 --> 00:31:16,277
Scott: Either the zeros and ones make it to the other end, or they don't.

443
00:31:16,317 --> 00:31:18,360
Scott: You can't interfere with the zeros and ones.

444
00:31:18,501 --> 00:31:23,720
Rym: Because if you interfere with them, that means that there's such a powerful interference that no cable would have worked.

445
00:31:24,400 --> 00:31:25,904
Scott: And that it'll just not work.

446
00:31:25,944 --> 00:31:28,511
Scott: You won't hear, like, your music won't get messed up.

447
00:31:28,752 --> 00:31:31,740
Scott: You just won't hear music, because the zeros and ones won't make it.

448
00:31:32,160 --> 00:31:37,858
Scott: I mean, if I sent you an MP3 that's missing a few ones and zeros, you can't play it in your MP3 player.

449
00:31:37,958 --> 00:31:38,460
Scott: It won't work.

450
00:31:39,020 --> 00:31:44,600
Scott: That's what happens if zeros and ones go missing, which means someone probably cut your cable with a scissor or a knife or something.

451
00:31:45,761 --> 00:31:54,080
Rym: So, despite this, whenever you go to a place like Circuit City or Best Buy, the salesmen are told, they're trained, they must try to sell you the Monster cables.

452
00:31:54,480 --> 00:31:57,047
