466
00:33:20,400 --> 00:33:22,022
Scott: Yep, let me give you an example.

467
00:33:22,243 --> 00:33:35,260
Scott: If you plug your computer's power supply directly into the wall, you know, the fact that the power isn't perfect will probably, over time, over a long period of time, eventually cause your power supply in your computer to stop functioning.

468
00:33:35,560 --> 00:33:38,551
Rym: Because when there are sudden voltage drops, the power supply has to make up for it.

469
00:33:38,611 --> 00:33:41,040
Rym: When there's little surges, the power supply has to deal with it.

470
00:33:41,260 --> 00:33:41,540
Rym: Yes,

471
00:33:42,041 --> 00:34:01,540
Scott: but if you had a UPS, which is basically a battery, in between your computer and the wall, that battery will handle it whenever the wall isn't perfect, and as far as your power supply in your computer is concerned, everything is perfect, because the battery is, you know, a nice little buffer, and everything's taken care of.

472
00:34:02,261 --> 00:34:03,444
Rym: Yes, I mean, think of it this way.

473
00:34:03,824 --> 00:34:08,755
