00:41:05,880 --> 00:41:10,293
Rym: If you live anywhere near a geek, or you live near the Geek House here, give us a call.

573
00:41:10,534 --> 00:41:12,600
Rym: I'll make you any frickin' ethernet cable you want.

574
00:41:12,840 --> 00:41:13,021
Rym: Yeah.

575
00:41:13,563 --> 00:41:18,580
Scott: Alright, now there's one more lie that we want to talk about, and that is the lie of specifications.

576
00:41:18,880 --> 00:41:24,914
Rym: Now you might see, you know, someone sells a new HDTV, and they say, "Oh, it has a 8,000 to 1 contrast

577
00:41:24,934 --> 00:41:25,274
Rym: ratio.".

578
00:41:27,940 --> 00:41:37,818
Scott: Or you'll go and you'll buy a new LCD monitor, and they'll say, you know, "Contrast ratio this, color saturation somethin'

579
00:41:37,959 --> 00:41:38,119
Scott: else.".

580
00:41:38,821 --> 00:41:42,417
Scott: Or you'll buy a sound card, and they'll say, "Siggle the noise ratio

581
00:41:42,497 --> 00:41:42,859
Scott: somethin'.".

582
00:41:43,280 --> 00:41:52,220
Rym: The biggest problem was monitors, and at the peak of the CRT days, before LCDs were viable in any stretch, the-- Like, I think 1996, 1997.

583
00:41:52,220 --> 00:41:54,700
Rym: Yeah, that era, when they would say the dot pitch.

584
00:41:55,426 --> 00:41:55,658
Rym: Oh god.

585
00:41:55,700 --> 00:41:57,424
Rym: And they would give you the dot pitch of the monitor.

586
00:41:57,464 --> 00:42:02,477
Rym: Now, some statistics about technology are accurate representations.

587
00:42:02,497 --> 00:42:03,580
Rym: They're objective measures.

588
00:42:03,840 --> 00:42:08,034
Scott: For example, I would say, "This monitor supports a maximum resolution of

589
00:42:08,054 --> 00:42:08,075
Scott: 1280x1024.".

590
00:42:09,700 --> 00:42:10,452
Rym: That is objective.

591
00:42:10,493 --> 00:42:12,359
Rym: It cannot show-- At X number of hertz.

592
00:42:12,500 --> 00:42:15,360
Rym: It cannot show more than that many pixels at that many hertz.

593
00:42:15,501 --> 00:42:16,019
Scott: At that speed.

594
00:42:16,661 --> 00:42:20,137
Rym: Or, "This monitor requires this much power to

595
00:42:20,278 --> 00:42:20,639
Rym: operate.".

596
00:42:20,981 --> 00:42:24,439
Scott: Or, "This monitor has a DVI cable hole and a VGA

597
00:42:24,499 --> 00:42:24,660
Scott: hole.".

598
00:42:25,362 --> 00:42:27,751
Rym: Now, beyond that, contrast ratio.

599
00:42:27,791 --> 00:42:30,200
Rym: We'll use that first, 'cause that's the easiest one to just throw away.

600
00:42:30,420 --> 00:42:30,695
Scott: It is.

601
00:42:31,140 --> 00:42:39,780
Rym: Now, theoretically, it is the ratio of the difference between the brightest color a monitor can show and the blackest color a monitor can show.

602
00:42:39,900 --> 00:42:46,580
Scott: So, what you want in a contrast ratio of any display technology is a very high number and a very low number.

603
00:42:46,640 --> 00:42:50,780
Scott: 'Cause that means that when there is black on the screen, it will be pitch black.

604
00:42:50,981 --> 00:42:53,740
Scott: And when there is white on the screen, it will be white, white, white.

605
00:42:54,242 --> 00:42:59,520
Rym: Now, a lot of companies, especially lower-end or shadier ones, will advertise all sorts of different contrast ratios.

606
00:43:00,020 --> 00:43:11,800
Rym: The thing is, you have to bear in mind that with most of these non-purely objective statistics, there is absolutely no standard or regulatory control over how they advertise this.

607
00:43:12,160 --> 00:43:15,920
Rym: And every company can measure it in any cockamamie way they want.

608
00:43:16,200 --> 00:43:19,634
Scott: Yeah, so one company says, "Oh, this is how we measure contrast ratio.

609
00:43:19,875 --> 00:43:20,377
Scott: We use this

610
00:43:20,458 --> 00:43:20,759
Scott: method.".

611
00:43:21,100 --> 00:43:23,575
Scott: "And then we round off to the nearest thousandth, and then

612
00:43:23,615 --> 00:43:23,816
Scott: this.".

613
00:43:24,460 --> 00:43:28,058
Scott: And, you know, they give you a number like, "Oh, this thing has an 8,000 to 1 contrast

614
00:43:28,078 --> 00:43:28,420
Scott: ratio.".

615
00:43:28,480 --> 00:43:31,935
Scott: And another company measures some other monitor, and they say, "This one has a 6,000 to

616
00:43:31,935 --> 00:43:33,120
Scott: 1.".

617
00:43:33,120 --> 00:43:38,560
Scott: But the 6,000 to 1 actually looks better and has a darker black and a brighter white than the 8,000 to 1.

618
00:43:38,560 --> 00:43:38,620
Rym: Yep.

619
00:43:38,680 --> 00:43:40,588
Rym: And sometimes, they'll straight-up lie.

620
00:43:40,849 --> 00:43:42,596
Rym: They really will, especially some shady companies.

621
00:43:42,616 --> 00:43:43,640
Rym: They'll just make up numbers.

622
00:43:43,900 --> 00:43:47,435
Scott: Yeah, they'll be like, "Oh yeah, this thing has a 10 hajillion to 1 contrast ratio.

623
00:43:47,475 --> 00:43:48,198
Scott: It's the best thing in the

624
00:43:48,238 --> 00:43:48,579
Scott: universe.".

625
00:43:50,049 --> 00:43:50,820
Scott: Yeah, it's better.

626
00:43:51,900 --> 00:43:58,860
Scott: Also, when TVs are on the display floor, they often set the color settings to look really good on a display floor.

627
00:43:59,200 --> 00:44:07,320
Scott: But those aren't the settings you use at home, so don't trust the way the screen looks in the store as to how it's going to look in your house.

628
00:44:07,720 --> 00:44:07,921
Rym: Yep.

629
00:44:08,061 --> 00:44:13,360
Rym: In fact, I remember I read an article of exactly what they do to TVs in Best Buy, because someone leaked the document.

630
00:44:13,721 --> 00:44:13,981
Scott: Yeah.

631
00:44:14,402 --> 00:44:25,620
Scott: What you want to do is you want to go into the Best Buy, you want to pick up the remote, and reset the TV to the settings that you're going to use at home in a normal, you know, "watching a real movie" condition.

632
00:44:25,760 --> 00:44:35,600
Rym: Also, if you can, you want to put in any DVD or input other than what they're showing, because they show things that very specifically are designed to make the TVs look a lot sharper than they are.

633
00:44:35,860 --> 00:44:45,740
Scott: Yeah, they show cartoons with really bright colors, they show nature things, they show concerts with bright lights and fog, you know, they show super epic Hollywood movies.

634
00:44:46,240 --> 00:44:53,035
Scott: Go grab yourself like a normal DVD from the shelf, you know, of like an 80s movie or something, or an anime, and put that in there.

635
00:44:53,476 --> 00:44:55,320
Scott: And then you'll be able to tell what's going on.

636
00:44:56,202 --> 00:44:57,786
Rym: Now, dot pitch was another big one.

637
00:44:57,807 --> 00:45:02,580
Rym: It's not so much of an issue now, because with LCD monitors it's really an irrelevant statistic.

638
00:45:03,040 --> 00:45:03,160
Rym: Yep.

639
00:45:03,200 --> 00:45:11,035
Rym: But it's the, especially on CRTs and televisions, it is basically the distance between the pixels, or between the colors.

640
00:45:11,656 --> 00:45:13,740
Rym: Now I say "or" because that's tricky.

641
00:45:13,960 --> 00:45:18,371
Rym: I mean, on CRTs you usually have three different phosphors for every pixel.

642
00:45:19,013 --> 00:45:21,780
Rym: So did they measure from the center of those three to the center of the other three?

643
00:45:22,181 --> 00:45:23,123
Rym: What if they're in a line?

644
00:45:23,343 --> 00:45:28,013
Rym: Do they measure it diagonally, up and down, horizontally, vertically, backwards?

645
00:45:28,714 --> 00:45:31,640
Rym: There are so many ways to do it that the statistic becomes meaningless.

646
00:45:32,540 --> 00:45:36,400
Scott: There are lots of other different measurements for different products, not just display technologies.

647
00:45:36,420 --> 00:45:38,800
Rym: Like even processors, the megahertz.

648
00:45:39,400 --> 00:45:47,580
Scott: Yeah, well, megahertz is a pretty solid measurement in and of itself, but the megahertz is not directly proportional to the speed of the computer.

649
00:45:48,182 --> 00:45:54,940
Scott: I can get, if you want, I can go find a one gigahertz processor that's faster than a one and a half gigahertz processor.

650
00:45:55,200 --> 00:46:00,308
Rym: See, because first we talked about statistics and data that are either useless or outright lies.

651
00:46:00,669 --> 00:46:07,960
Rym: There's also the case where there is data that is perfectly verifiable and legitimate, but people will grossly overstate or understate the significance.

652
00:46:08,100 --> 00:46:17,800
Rym: Like say there's mega blobs and a fleam has eight mega blobs, but this other company's fleam has nine mega blobs.

653
00:46:18,580 --> 00:46:21,128
Rym: Now, what's the difference of one mega blob?

654
00:46:21,388 --> 00:46:23,635
Rym: I mean, is one mega blob something that you'll notice?

655
00:46:23,976 --> 00:46:25,300
Rym: Is it something inconsequential?

656
00:46:25,921 --> 00:46:28,600
Scott: Is it worth the difference in price between the two products?

657
00:46:28,880 --> 00:46:29,783
Rym: Is it even measurable?

658
00:46:29,943 --> 00:46:31,448
Rym: It could just be a statistical coincidence.

659
00:46:31,468 --> 00:46:35,660
Rym: I mean, a really important thing here is the idea of statistical significance.

660
00:46:36,461 --> 00:46:49,760
Rym: Not going to go over it because none of you care, but you can analyze data and based on the data and the data set and various calculus, you can figure out how reliable or accurate or useful the data you have is.

661
00:46:50,460 --> 00:47:00,299
Rym: So you'll be able to say like within a precision of 5% in either direction, we are 95% sure that this number is within 5% of this number or something like that.

662
00:47:01,261 --> 00:47:13,680
Rym: Below that, a number is not statistically significant, meaning you can't reasonably draw a conclusion based on the number because the difference in the number is so negligible that it's not differentiable from static.

663
00:47:14,540 --> 00:47:19,910
Scott: Yeah, it's like this monitor has a 5 and the other monitor has a 4.9.

664
00:47:19,910 --> 00:47:21,994
Scott: Well, is the 5 better than the 4.9?

665
00:47:21,994 --> 00:47:24,199
Scott: We don't know because we might have measured the 4.9 wrong.

666
00:47:24,920 --> 00:47:27,006
Scott: It might actually be a 5.3.

667
00:47:27,006 --> 00:47:31,500
Scott: It could just be noise rate randomness in the measuring process.

668
00:47:31,700 --> 00:47:33,002
Rym: I mean, think in first person shooters.

669
00:47:33,382 --> 00:47:38,951
Rym: I mean, the difference between 10 frames per second and 20 frames per second is insane.

670
00:47:39,451 --> 00:47:45,320
Rym: The difference between 100 frames a second and 500 is undetectable by human eyes.

671
00:47:46,300 --> 00:47:46,821
Scott: Exactly.

672
00:47:46,982 --> 00:47:53,596
Scott: Even though if someone came up and told you this thing is 500 frames a second and that one's only 100, you'd be like, "Holy crap, it's five times

673
00:47:53,657 --> 00:47:53,877
Scott: better.".

674
00:47:53,917 --> 00:47:55,140
Scott: No, it's zero times better.

675
00:47:56,000 --> 00:47:58,083
Rym: Now, with technology, the advice isn't so easy.

676
00:47:58,103 --> 00:48:06,437
Rym: Well, with technology like that, it's not as easy as, "Don't listen to the salespeople, don't buy any cables in the store," because there's really no one.

677
00:48:06,457 --> 00:48:07,338
Rym: You just have to ask a geek.

678
00:48:07,699 --> 00:48:08,560
Rym: I hate to say that, but...

679
00:48:08,600 --> 00:48:16,474
Scott: Well, what you can also do is before you buy any consumer electronic product, you want to research not any specific product.

680
00:48:16,754 --> 00:48:19,860
Scott: You want to research that variety of product itself.

681
00:48:19,960 --> 00:48:24,727
Scott: So if you're in the market for an HDTV, research HDTVs.

682
00:48:24,847 --> 00:48:28,012
Scott: Learn everything you can about HDTV technology.

683
00:48:28,593 --> 00:48:33,760
Scott: And don't get your information from any company that sells HDTVs, like Best Buy or Circuit City.

684
00:48:34,201 --> 00:48:40,108
Scott: Don't get your information from any company that makes HDTVs, like, I don't know, Samsung or Sony or anyone.

685
00:48:40,608 --> 00:48:49,118
Scott: Get your information from independent, geek sources that talk about the technology itself, like in Gadget or us or someone, anywhere.

686
00:48:49,399 --> 00:48:50,440
Rym: Wikipedia even.

687
00:48:50,841 --> 00:48:52,222
Rym: Keep in mind that we do this, too.

688
00:48:52,343 --> 00:49:02,597
Rym: When I bought my first, when I built my first computer, before I went to RIT, I spent over two months researching every single component and learning everything I could about them.

689
00:49:02,617 --> 00:49:04,800
Rym: I learned about all the different kinds of RAM and chipsets.

690
00:49:04,980 --> 00:49:08,580
Scott: I had a one-year subscription to Computer Shopper just to learn all that stuff.

691
00:49:09,021 --> 00:49:18,533
Rym: I mean, I would read about how sound cards worked in detail, so then when I went to the store and I looked at two sound cards, I could say to myself, "Wow, this one is clearly superior.

692
00:49:18,713 --> 00:49:19,314
Rym: I will purchase

693
00:49:19,354 --> 00:49:19,414
Rym: it.".

694
00:49:19,555 --> 00:49:22,719
Rym: Or, "This one is only slightly superior but costs ten times as much.

695
00:49:22,759 --> 00:49:22,999
Rym: This is

696
00:49:23,039 --> 00:49:23,420
Rym: bullshit.".

697
00:49:23,760 --> 00:49:32,876
Scott: Yes, if you are less knowledgeable than the Best Buy and Circuit City employees, they are going to fool you and you're going to end up getting ripped off and buying some monster cables.

698
00:49:33,357 --> 00:49:35,020
Scott: You have to know more than they do.

699
00:49:35,160 --> 00:49:36,241
Scott: I mean, it's sad.

700
00:49:36,382 --> 00:49:51,380
Scott: I wish, I really wish that I didn't have to know more than them because I wish that the Best Buy and Circuit City employees were experts who knew everything about technology and were honest and would share the truth and really help you find the best product at the best price.

701
00:49:51,500 --> 00:49:53,388
Rym: The problem is that's not economically viable.

702
00:49:53,709 --> 00:49:56,380
Rym: You make much more money by selling schlock to idiots.

703
00:49:56,782 --> 00:49:58,820
Scott: And having idiots sell schlock to idiots.

704
00:49:59,240 --> 00:49:59,320
Rym: Yes.

705
00:49:59,741 --> 00:50:04,428
Scott: If there was a store where there were, like, genius geeks running the store, that would be the best store in the world.

706
00:50:04,468 --> 00:50:05,810
Scott: I wouldn't have to research shit.

707
00:50:05,850 --> 00:50:06,651
Scott: It would be so great.

708
00:50:06,711 --> 00:50:11,438
Scott: I would go into the store and I would say, "Genius geeks who spend your life in this store.

709
00:50:11,498 --> 00:50:11,979
Scott: You know what to

710
00:50:12,019 --> 00:50:12,300
Scott: buy.".

711
00:50:12,620 --> 00:50:16,466
Rym: In fact, I remember the exact moment when I became disillusioned.

712
00:50:17,507 --> 00:50:20,151
Rym: I went to a computer store that no longer exists.

713
00:50:20,592 --> 00:50:22,454
Rym: And this was before I'd even built a computer.

714
00:50:22,474 --> 00:50:24,697
Rym: I mean, this is way back in the day.

715
00:50:24,938 --> 00:50:26,400
Rym: Windows NT had just come out.

716
00:50:27,241 --> 00:50:28,765
Rym: And I go to this big computer store.

717
00:50:29,045 --> 00:50:31,892
Rym: It was like a computer store and nothing more.

718
00:50:32,272 --> 00:50:35,059
Rym: They only sold computers and computer equipment.

719
00:50:35,139 --> 00:50:35,620
Rym: It was huge.

720
00:50:36,840 --> 00:50:38,403
Rym: And I found a salesman and I talked to him.

721
00:50:38,744 --> 00:50:43,473
Rym: And I said, "I want a dual CPU machine with Windows

722
00:50:43,654 --> 00:50:44,275
Rym: NT.".

723
00:50:44,616 --> 00:50:46,780
Rym: Because I'd read about Windows NT and I wanted to try it.

724
00:50:46,920 --> 00:50:48,905
Rym: And I had all these demands and things I wanted.

725
00:50:49,546 --> 00:50:51,631
Rym: And the guy stared at me like I was an idiot.

726
00:50:52,132 --> 00:50:55,360
Rym: And I don't think he even knew what I meant by dual CPU.

727
00:50:56,320 --> 00:50:58,463
Rym: And then he said, "You don't want Windows

728
00:50:58,564 --> 00:50:58,884
Rym: NT.".

729
00:50:58,904 --> 00:51:00,867
Rym: And I said, "Why

730
00:51:00,927 --> 00:51:01,147
Rym: not?".

731
00:51:01,167 --> 00:51:03,010
Rym: And he said, "No one uses Windows NT.

732
00:51:03,531 --> 00:51:04,632
Rym: It's too hard to use.

733
00:51:04,692 --> 00:51:04,792
Rym: It's

734
00:51:04,853 --> 00:51:05,353
Rym: expensive.".

735
00:51:05,413 --> 00:51:07,977
Rym: I said, "But I want Windows NT.

736
00:51:08,398 --> 00:51:10,040
Rym: I know all about it and I want to run

737
00:51:10,060 --> 00:51:10,100
Rym: it.".

738
00:51:10,100 --> 00:51:11,605
Rym: And he said, "You don't want Windows

739
00:51:11,706 --> 00:51:11,987
Rym: NT.".

740
00:51:13,191 --> 00:51:15,580
Rym: And that was really pretty much the end of that day of shopping.

741
00:51:16,664 --> 00:51:17,439
Scott: Yes, it was.

742
00:51:18,101 --> 00:51:21,100
Rym: I mean, I wish I was exaggerating or making that up, but that's what happened.

743
00:51:23,281 --> 00:51:23,602
Scott: Yeah, yeah.

744
00:51:23,783 --> 00:51:26,250
Scott: I mean, the more expensive product is clearly superior.

745
00:51:26,270 --> 00:51:26,792
Scott: Alright.

746
00:51:30,420 --> 00:51:35,080
Rym: Yeah, I think we're done, but people did complain that the show cuts off abruptly, so now I'm going to ramble for a little bit.

747
00:51:35,500 --> 00:51:38,360
Scott: Well, I think I just want to talk a little bit more about some of the audiophile stuff.

748
00:51:38,841 --> 00:51:40,459
Rym: Alright, we've gone on a bit long, though, so.

749
00:51:40,700 --> 00:51:49,360
Scott: Alright, because at the beginning we kind of brushed it off, but there is a lot of stuff out there in audiophile technology which is just completely false.

750
00:51:49,500 --> 00:51:54,689
Scott: Like, we're not even talking about, you know, they lie about the numbers or they overcharge.

751
00:51:54,729 --> 00:52:01,580
Scott: We're talking about this is a speaker that, you know, they'll say this wooden volume knob will make your stereo sound better.

752
00:52:01,580 --> 00:52:02,162
Scott: We're not kidding.

753
00:52:02,624 --> 00:52:04,673
Rym: That was a very specific product.

754
00:52:04,894 --> 00:52:06,200
Rym: In fact, it had imitators.

755
00:52:06,680 --> 00:52:13,860
Scott: Yeah, or they'll say these crystals, if you put these crystals or you put this sticker on the side of your speakers, it'll make it sound more natural.

756
00:52:14,381 --> 00:52:18,833
Rym: I read someone's blog, and it was an audiophile, and he'd talk about it with an audiophile friend.

757
00:52:18,894 --> 00:52:21,079
Rym: It was linked to, in fact, from the JREF a while ago.

758
00:52:21,860 --> 00:52:27,200
Rym: And this guy was testing sound with someone in a room with an oak table in the room and a turntable.

759
00:52:27,600 --> 00:52:37,460
Rym: And, you know, they were comparing the various between this diamond-tipped needle and this other slightly different diamond-tipped needle and this power cable versus this power cable and all sorts of masturbatory bullshit.

760
00:52:38,540 --> 00:52:41,603
Rym: And the worst part is that these people will lie to each other and themselves.

761
00:52:42,003 --> 00:52:50,711
Rym: They will convince themselves that they hear the difference, thus justifying their purchase, and thus they can say to other people, "Oh, of course you couldn't hear it.

762
00:52:50,871 --> 00:52:52,333
Rym: I have the golden ear.

763
00:52:52,653 --> 00:53:00,280
Rym: My ears are so attuned to the wonderful nature of music that I can hear the slightest disturbance in the sound and blah blah blah blah blah blah

764
00:53:00,320 --> 00:53:00,580
Rym: blah.".

765
00:53:01,161 --> 00:53:03,324
Scott: Yes, there are people selling products.

766
00:53:03,384 --> 00:53:13,140
Scott: If anyone tries to sell you anything, and they say that it will make your music sound better, unless it's like a dollar, they're probably lying to you.

767
00:53:13,460 --> 00:53:16,627
Scott: Yes, I mean-- They're probably just selling something that does nothing.

768
00:53:16,647 --> 00:53:20,799
Scott: A wooden volume knob does nothing except make your volume knob look like wood.

769
00:53:21,561 --> 00:53:23,464
Rym: I mean, there are high-end audio things.

770
00:53:23,504 --> 00:53:29,694
Rym: I mean, I could buy a $400 pair of monitor headphones that is absolutely perfect in every way.

771
00:53:30,495 --> 00:53:31,757
Rym: These people will buy $4,000 ones.

772
00:53:34,260 --> 00:53:36,620
Scott: That are perfect in every way, but no different.

773
00:53:36,800 --> 00:53:45,280
Rym: In fact, many times, this audiophile stuff is actually worse because the people buying it can't actually tell, and you make so much more money by making it cheaply and quickly.

774
00:53:45,921 --> 00:53:50,505
Scott: Yeah, like, some guy will say, "Oh, I made this cable out of gold.

775
00:53:50,805 --> 00:54:04,919
Scott: It makes everything sound so much better, and it has a platinum core, and it's only $7,000 for this incredibly amazing cable that will allow no interference and transmit perfect analog audio from your analog amplifier to your

776
00:54:05,379 --> 00:54:05,840
Scott: speakers.".

777
00:54:06,441 --> 00:54:10,176
Scott: And some crazy audiophile will go, "Oh my god, I bought it, and I can totally hear the difference.

778
00:54:10,196 --> 00:54:10,879
Scott: This is the greatest thing

779
00:54:10,939 --> 00:54:11,080
